# Conclusion

In this analysis, we examined the relationship between environmental concern and various demographic and socioeconomic variables using linear regression models. We developed the model using a stepwise additive process, and in the final multivariate model, most of the predictors were significant with a multiple R-squared that ecplained about 22% of the variance in the outcome variable, environmental attitudes.

We also conducted a Principal Component Analysis (PCA) on the environmental attitudes variables to reduce dimensionality and identify the most important components that explain the variance in the dataset. The PCA revealed that the first principal component accounted for the largest proportion of variance in the data, followed by subsequent components that explained decreasing amounts of variance. 

Following the PCA, we conducted an exploratory factor analysis. While the results of the EFA were mostly moot, it confirmed that the first factor in the PCA was the best fit. Lastly, we conducted a CFA that confirmed the explanatory power of the latent variable 'environmental attitudes' in explaining the variance of the 5 components.

Overall, this analysis provides valuable insights into the factors that influence environmental concern and contributes to our understanding of the complex interplay between individual characteristics and attitudes towards the environment. Future research could explore additional variables and interactions between them in the ISSP 2020 ENV data to further refine the model and enhance our understanding of environmental attitudes. The work we have done here lays the basis for more advanced modeling techniques, such as Structural Equation Modeling. 

